<subSubSection lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="76" pageId="14" pageNumber="75" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1364,2038]" pageId="14" pageNumber="75">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1437,1462]" pageId="14" pageNumber="75">Description.</emphasis>
Based mainly on largest complete animal, 0.8 mm long, 0.3 wide, 13 segments. Body very small, rectangular, pale yellow to orange. Paleae fans yellow to golden, imbricated over dorsum. Prostomium visible among the first two anterior segments. Two small lateral antennae partially visible on anterior margin of prostomium; a subulate median antenna, larger than lateral antennae (about three times lateral antenna length). Two pairs of violet eyes, first pair smaller than second; in some specimens the eyes are jointed longitudinally, making the ocular spot seems rectangular. Nuchal fold absent. Two palps almost circular, visible in ventral view. Muscular and circular mouth fold posterior to palps; eversible proboscis with two short and slim transparent stylets.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1364,2038]" lastBlockId="15.[151,1437,151,572]" lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="76" pageId="14" pageNumber="75">
Parapodium from the ninth segment. Notochaetae separated in three main groups and one subgroup (
<figureCitation box="[1333,1423,1689,1714]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1941,1963]" captionTargetBox="[180,1399,205,1900]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[164,1422,193,1919]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 9. Hyalopale sp. A, parapodium middle segment; B–E, neurochaetal types; F, lateral palea (spine); G, subunit 1 palea; H, main palea; I–K, median palea. Scale bars: 20 µm (BCDEF), 30 µm (GHI), 100 µm (A)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2609686/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="75">Fig. 9A</figureCitation>
). Lateral group inserted just below of notoaciculum; including one slender curved spine without ribs (
<figureCitation box="[1296,1383,1725,1750]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1941,1963]" captionTargetBox="[180,1399,205,1900]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[164,1422,193,1919]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 9. Hyalopale sp. A, parapodium middle segment; B–E, neurochaetal types; F, lateral palea (spine); G, subunit 1 palea; H, main palea; I–K, median palea. Scale bars: 20 µm (BCDEF), 30 µm (GHI), 100 µm (A)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2609686/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="75">Fig. 9F</figureCitation>
). As sub-unit 1, one almost symmetrical and slightly serrated palea with 16–22 ribs and four raised ribs (
<figureCitation box="[1267,1357,1761,1786]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1941,1963]" captionTargetBox="[180,1399,205,1900]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[164,1422,193,1919]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 9. Hyalopale sp. A, parapodium middle segment; B–E, neurochaetal types; F, lateral palea (spine); G, subunit 1 palea; H, main palea; I–K, median palea. Scale bars: 20 µm (BCDEF), 30 µm (GHI), 100 µm (A)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2609686/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="75">Fig. 9G</figureCitation>
). Main group, comprising 9–12 wide, long and asymmetrical paleae with 21–28 ribs and 4–6 raised ribs finely serrated (
<figureCitation box="[159,249,1833,1858]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1941,1963]" captionTargetBox="[180,1399,205,1900]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[164,1422,193,1919]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 9. Hyalopale sp. A, parapodium middle segment; B–E, neurochaetal types; F, lateral palea (spine); G, subunit 1 palea; H, main palea; I–K, median palea. Scale bars: 20 µm (BCDEF), 30 µm (GHI), 100 µm (A)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2609686/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="75">Fig. 9H</figureCitation>
). When present, median group comprising one curved and almost symmetrical paleae, with 15–18 ribs and 5–6 raised ribs (
<figureCitation box="[329,408,1869,1894]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1941,1963]" captionTargetBox="[180,1399,205,1900]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[164,1422,193,1919]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 9. Hyalopale sp. A, parapodium middle segment; B–E, neurochaetal types; F, lateral palea (spine); G, subunit 1 palea; H, main palea; I–K, median palea. Scale bars: 20 µm (BCDEF), 30 µm (GHI), 100 µm (A)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2609686/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="75">
Fig. 
<date box="[381,408,1869,1893]" pageId="14" pageNumber="75">9I</date>
</figureCitation>
). Every paleae in these groups showing a serrated edge and a hooked final tip, except for the lateral group. Neuropodium small and cylindrical. Heterogomph neurochaetae composed of four groups (
<figureCitation box="[1337,1402,1905,1930]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1941,1963]" captionTargetBox="[180,1399,205,1900]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[164,1422,193,1919]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 9. Hyalopale sp. A, parapodium middle segment; B–E, neurochaetal types; F, lateral palea (spine); G, subunit 1 palea; H, main palea; I–K, median palea. Scale bars: 20 µm (BCDEF), 30 µm (GHI), 100 µm (A)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2609686/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="75">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
B– E). Neurochaetigers with 2–3 superior spinigers, with long, slim curved blades. Presence of superior spinigers increasing in the first three segments. Mid-superior group with 7–9 falcigers with medium length blades (2/3 of spiniger blade length) and serration basally. Mid-inferior group with 6–8 falcigers with medium to short blades (1/2 of spiniger blade length), serration basally. Inferior group of 2–4 falcigers with short and smooth blades (2/7 of spiniger blade length) with fine serration basally. Every blade of falcigers ending in a terminal claw. Pygidium rounded, with two reduced anal cirri.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,151,572]" box="[199,1121,260,285]" pageId="15" pageNumber="76">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,298,260,285]" pageId="15" pageNumber="76">Habitat.</emphasis>
Subtidal (
<quantity box="[413,489,260,284]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="76" unit="m" value="3.0" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.0">2–4 m</quantity>
). These specimens were collected on algae (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Adanson" authorityYear="1763" box="[986,1067,260,284]" class="Phaeophyceae" family="Dictyotaceae" genus="Padina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Dictyotales" pageId="15" pageNumber="76" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[986,1067,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="76">Padina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp.).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
